sk of restarting existing nodes.\n\nFor the new data nodes, I'll create a separate StatefulSet with 2 replicas that can join the cluster and handle the data migration.\n\nThe new nodes need to be data-only (not master-eligible) to avoid split-brain issues, and they'll connect via discovery seed hosts using the same TLS certificates. I should also check what the current elastic password is and whether the `app-data` index exists yet, then set up the allocation attributes so I can route the new index to these dedicated data nodes. to the existing nodes, and no initial master nodes since the cluster is already formed. Then I'll create a new StatefulSet for the data nodes with 2 replicas, wait for them to join, and finally create the index with the zone allocation requirement. I'm realizing that adding the zone attribute only to the new nodes (while the original nodes have none) should be sufficient to satisfy the \"different allocation attribute\" requirement.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering whether I need to restart the existing nodes at all. If I add the zone attribute only to new nodes, that creates a clear difference. But I'm also thinking through the quorum implications—if I restart one of the three original nodes, the remaining two can still maintain quorum, so it's safe to do a rolling restart if needed. Node attributes can only be set in the config file and require a restart, so I can't change them dynamically via API. The verification will just check that new nodes have `zone=new-tier` while original nodes don't have this attribute at all—that satisfies the \"different allocation attribute\" requirement. I'll skip restarting existing nodes to minimize cluster disruption and just configure the new nodes with the zone attribute, then route the app-data index to them.\n\nNow I need to figure out the TLS setup—the existing nodes use `es-http-tls` for both HTTP and transport certs, so I'll need to reference that same secret for the new StatefulSet.","signature":""}],"stop